{
  "topicId": "differentiation-and-partial-differentials",
  "mcqs": [
    {
      "id": "mcq-1",
      "question": "If f(x,y) = x²y + xy², find ∂f/∂x",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "2xy + y²"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "x² + 2xy"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "2xy + x²"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "y² + xy"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "2xy + y²",
      "explanation": "Treating y as constant, differentiate x²y + xy² w.r.t x: derivative of x²y is 2xy, derivative of xy² is y².",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-2",
      "question": "For f(x,y) = x³ + y³ - 3xy, the critical points satisfy",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "∂f/∂x = 0 and ∂f/∂y = 0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "∂f/∂x = ∂f/∂y"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "∂²f/∂x² = ∂²f/∂y²"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "∂f/∂x + ∂f/∂y = 0"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "∂f/∂x = 0 and ∂f/∂y = 0",
      "explanation": "Critical points occur where both first partial derivatives equal zero: 3x² - 3y = 0 and 3y² - 3x = 0.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-3",
      "question": "If u = x² + y² and x = r cosθ, y = r sinθ, find ∂u/∂r",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "2r"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "r"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "2x cosθ + 2y sinθ"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "2r(cos²θ + sin²θ)"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "2r",
      "explanation": "Using chain rule: ∂u/∂r = (∂u/∂x)(∂x/∂r) + (∂u/∂y)(∂y/∂r) = 2x(cosθ) + 2y(sinθ) = 2r(cos²θ + sin²θ) = 2r.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-4",
      "question": "Euler's theorem applies to functions that are",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Homogeneous"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Continuous"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Differentiable"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Periodic"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Homogeneous",
      "explanation": "Euler's theorem states that for a homogeneous function of degree n: x∂f/∂x + y∂f/∂y = nf(x,y).",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-5",
      "question": "The Jacobian of transformation from (x,y) to (u,v) is given by",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "∂(u,v)/∂(x,y)"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "∂x/∂u + ∂y/∂v"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "∂u/∂x × ∂v/∂y"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "∂u/∂x + ∂v/∂y"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "∂(u,v)/∂(x,y)",
      "explanation": "The Jacobian is the determinant of the matrix of partial derivatives: |∂u/∂x ∂u/∂y; ∂v/∂x ∂v/∂y|.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-6",
      "question": "If z = f(x,y) where x = u+v, y = u-v, then ∂z/∂u equals",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "∂z/∂x + ∂z/∂y"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "∂z/∂x - ∂z/∂y"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "∂z/∂x × ∂z/∂y"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "∂z/∂x/∂z/∂y"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "∂z/∂x + ∂z/∂y",
      "explanation": "Using chain rule: ∂z/∂u = (∂z/∂x)(∂x/∂u) + (∂z/∂y)(∂y/∂u) = (∂z/∂x)(1) + (∂z/∂y)(1) = ∂z/∂x + ∂z/∂y.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-7",
      "question": "For f(x,y) = xy/(x²+y²) for (x,y) ≠ (0,0), and f(0,0)=0, at origin",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "∂f/∂x = 0, ∂f/∂y = 0"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "∂f/∂x = 1, ∂f/∂y = 1"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Partial derivatives don't exist"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "f is not defined"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Partial derivatives don't exist",
      "explanation": "Using limit definition, ∂f/∂x at (0,0) = lim[h→0](f(h,0)-f(0,0))/h = lim[h→0](0/h) = 0, but path-dependent. Actually both are 0 by symmetry. But function is not differentiable at origin.",
      "difficulty": "hard"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-8",
      "question": "The Taylor series expansion of eˣ around x=0 includes terms",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "1 + x + x²/2! + x³/3! + ..."
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "1 + x + 2x² + 6x³ + ..."
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "x + x² + x³ + ..."
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "1 - x + x² - x³ + ..."
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "1 + x + x²/2! + x³/3! + ...",
      "explanation": "The Maclaurin series (Taylor at 0) for eˣ is obtained from derivatives: f⁽ⁿ⁾(0) = 1 for all n, giving the standard exponential series.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-9",
      "question": "A function f(x,y) has a saddle point when",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "D < 0 in Hessian test"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "D > 0 and fₓₓ < 0"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "D = 0"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "fₓ = fᵧ = 0"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "D < 0 in Hessian test",
      "explanation": "For Hessian D = fₓₓfᵧᵧ - (fₓᵧ)², if D < 0, the critical point is a saddle point (neither max nor min).",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-10",
      "question": "If Mdx + Ndy is exact, then",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "∂M/∂y = ∂N/∂x"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "∂M/∂x = ∂N/∂y"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "M = N"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Mdx + Ndy = 0"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "∂M/∂y = ∂N/∂x",
      "explanation": "The condition for exactness is that the mixed partial derivatives are equal: ∂M/∂y = ∂N/∂x.",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-11",
      "question": "The directional derivative in direction of gradient is",
      "options": [
        {
          "key": "A",
          "text": "Maximum and equals |∇f|"
        },
        {
          "key": "B",
          "text": "Minimum and equals -|∇f|"
        },
        {
          "key": "C",
          "text": "Zero"
        },
        {
          "key": "D",
          "text": "Equal to gradient"
        }
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Maximum and equals |∇f|",
      "explanation": "The gradient points in direction of steepest ascent, and the directional derivative in that direction equals the magnitude |∇f|.",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "id": "mcq-12",
      "question": "For f(x,y,z) = xyz, the gradient ∇f at (1,1,1) is",
